## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow

### Why it breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). The cooperative cancellation model replaces all of this.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancelAfter replaces the manual Thread.Abort timeout pattern
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run + WaitAsync replaces Thread + Join + Abort
            return Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)   // .NET 6+ API
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must cooperate

The version above cancels the *wait*, but the work may keep running on the thread pool. If the work **must actually stop**, pass the token into it:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter()
                   .GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token at regular checkpoints:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work keeps running after "timeout"** | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` abandons the wait but the delegate keeps executing on the thread pool. You **must** pass the token into `work` and check it for true cancellation. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timer leaks if not disposed. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, raw socket reads, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If the work can't be modified to check the token, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — there is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |

### What was removed and why

| Old API | Replacement | Reason |
|---------|-------------|--------|
| `Thread` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run()` | Thread pool is more efficient; tasks compose better |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellable, non-blocking wait (`.NET 6+`) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative cancellation — no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No concept of "reset" — check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |
